      <body>
         <div type="edition">
         <!--The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements-->
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <persName>
                  <name key="Ἀθαία Aththaia">Ἀθ<surplus>θ</surplus>αία</name>
                  <lb n="2"/>
                  <name key="Malchos Μάλχος">Μάλχου</name>
               </persName>
               <lb n="3"/>ἄλ<unclear>υ</unclear>πε
               <lb n="4"/>χαῖρε.
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Aththaia, daughter of Malchos, free from pain, farewell.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary"><p>Line 3: may be read as ἄλυπε, which as an adjective is modifying Ἀθθαῖα. No interpuncts
            between words or at the end of lines. Aththaia wears various necklaces,
            including a crescent and sun pendant necklace, bracelets, rings, and a headband
            (diadem). The headband (diadem) was typical of the eastern Mediterranean.
            Aththaia wears a himation, which covers her body and head, over a chiton
            (tunic) Aththaia appears to grasp either a bunch of her himation or a fibula,
            which has its origins as jewelry in Britain before becoming popular in the
            western Mediterranean, but rare in the eastern Mediterranean. The abundance of
            jewelry on the figure is perhaps unsurprising given Palymra’s history as a
            center of jewelry production. The use of Greek rather than Aramaic is noteworthy
            and perhaps represents Greek influence in the region.</p>
            <p>The name Ἀθθαῖα is unattested in the online Lexicon of Greek Personal Names; additionally, the two thetas are likely dittography.</p>
               <p>Dating should be placed at about 150-200 CE, based
            on dress </p></div>
